  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Rather, it is a matter of seeing what happens as structured towards an identifiable end -something that seems to lie very deep in our capacity to respond to each other as a special kind of causal agent.We call on this capacity when we construct philosophical thought experiments involving deviant causal chains (Stout, 2010; Ward, 2024).",
    "One famous example, introduced by Davidson (2001a, ch. 4), concerns a climber faced with the decision whether or not to let go of the rope that connects him a dangling fellow climber.",
    "The climber reasons that he must release the rope in order to save his own life.",
    "However, rather than this process of thought terminating in what we would call his action -releasing the rope and allowing the fellow climber to fall to his deathwhat causally brings about just this series of events is a jolt, physically indistinguishable from the act of releasing the rope, caused by his horror at the momentousness of what he's about to do.",
    "The problem for the standard story here is that the both the causal and the rationalising condition for the act seem to have been met, but we nonetheless intuit that what happened is not an intentional action of the climber."
  ],
